From: Kamil Bienkiewicz <perceivalpercy@gmail.com>
Date: Fri, 29 May 2026 07:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] net: ethernet: qcom: ppe: xgmac enable MTL store-and-forward

The IPQ5332 XGMAC powers up with the MTL transmit FIFO in cut-through
mode (TSF=0) and a small Transmit Threshold (TTC). On this SoC that
combination causes the MAC to start transmitting as soon as a few
dozen bytes are in the TX FIFO; for anything bigger than a tiny frame
the rest of the payload does not arrive at the FIFO in time and the
MAC reports `tx_underflow_err` and drops the frame on the wire. The
behaviour is sharp and reproducible from userspace:

    size 64    10/10 received (100%)
    size 200   3/10 received (30%)
    size 500   0/10 received (100% loss)
    size 1000  0/10 received (100% loss)
    size 1400  0/10 received (100% loss)

`ip -s link show eth0` (and `/proc/net/dev`) tracks the count exactly:
one TX error + one TX fifo error per failed frame, because the
`tx_errors` accounting uses `xgmib_tx_underflow_err` as its source.
Confirmed it is not an offload bug (disabling NETIF_F_HW_CSUM +
NETIF_F_TSO did not help), not an MTU issue (smaller MTU did not
help), and not an AXI burst-length issue (toggling EDMA_DMAR_BURST_LEN
made things worse).

The fix is to take the XGMAC out of cut-through mode by setting
TSF=1 (Store-and-Forward) in MTL_TXQ_OPERATION_MODE, register at
XGMAC_BASE + 0x1100. With Store-and-Forward, the MAC waits until the
full frame is buffered in the TX FIFO before driving the MII/SGMII,
which trivially avoids the underflow window. Also set TXQEN=2 so the
queue is enabled in 802.1Qav-style mode (the value the QSDK vendor
driver uses for the same register).

Applied after the regular XGMAC RX-enable in `ppe_port_xgmac_link_up`
so the queue config is in place before any frame is offered to the
MAC.

Validated on Flint 3:

    --- 192.168.1.2 ping statistics ---
    10 packets transmitted, 10 packets received, 0% packet loss
    (s=64, 200, 500, 1000, 1400 all 100%, sub-ms RTT)

    [  5]   0.00-10.09 sec   861 MBytes   716 Mbits/sec  receiver
    (`iperf3 -c 192.168.1.2 -t 10` -- 942 Mbit/s steady-state per
     1s sample, slightly lower averaged because of the first second
     of TCP slow-start; this is wire-rate for the 1 Gbps host NIC.)

After-fix MIB: eth0 TX errs=0 / TX fifo=0 over a full iperf3 run
(was 126/126 for a 50-frame mixed-size burst before).

Signed-off-by: Kamil Bienkiewicz <perceivalpercy@gmail.com>
---
--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/qualcomm/ppe/ppe_port.c
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/qualcomm/ppe/ppe_port.c
@@ -793,6 +793,30 @@ static int ppe_port_xgmac_link_up(struct ppe_port *ppe_port,
 	/* Enable XGMAC RX*/
 	ret = regmap_update_bits(ppe_dev->regmap, reg + XGMAC_RX_CONFIG_ADDR,
 				 XGMAC_RXEN, XGMAC_RXEN);
+	if (ret)
+		return ret;
+
+	/* MTL_TXQ0_OPERATION_MODE @ XGMAC_BASE+0x1100.
+	 * Set TSF=1 (Store-and-Forward) so the XGMAC buffers the entire
+	 * frame before transmitting. Without this, on this SoC TX FIFO
+	 * underflows for frames >~200 bytes -- XGMAC reports
+	 * tx_underflow_err and the frame is dropped before reaching the
+	 * switch. With TSF=1 the FIFO threshold (TTC) becomes irrelevant;
+	 * the MAC waits for the full frame and then sends at line rate.
+	 * Bits: TXQEN=2 (bits 3:2), TSF=1 (bit 1).
+	 */
+	{
+		u32 mtl_val;
+		u32 mtl_mask;
+		u32 mtl_reg = reg + 0x1100;
+
+		mtl_mask = GENMASK(3, 1);
+		mtl_val = BIT(1) | (2u << 2);  /* TSF=1, TXQEN=2 */
+		ret = regmap_update_bits(ppe_dev->regmap, mtl_reg,
+					 mtl_mask, mtl_val);
+		if (ret)
+			return ret;
+	}

 	return ret;
 }
